\title{Flox Builds}

\taxon{skill}

\meta{description}{Building and packaging applications with Flox. Use for manifest builds, Nix expression builds, sandbox modes, multi-stage builds, and packaging assets.}

\subtree{
\title{Flox Build System Guide}
\subtree{
\title{Build System Overview}
\p{Flox supports two build modes, each with its own strengths:}

\p{\strong{Manifest builds} enable you to define your build steps in your manifest and reuse your existing build scripts and toolchains. Flox manifests are declarative artifacts, expressed in TOML.}

\p{Manifest builds:}

\ul{
\li{Make it easy to get started, requiring few if any changes to your existing workflows}
\li{Can run inside a sandbox (using \code{\startverb sandbox = "pure"\stopverb}) for reproducible builds}
\li{Are best for getting going fast with existing projects}
}

\p{\strong{Nix expression builds} guarantee build-time reproducibility because they're both isolated and purely functional. Their learning curve is steeper because they require proficiency with the Nix language.}

\p{Nix expression builds:}

\ul{
\li{Are isolated by default. The Nix sandbox seals the build off from the host system, so no state leak ins}
\li{Are functional. A Nix build is defined as a pure function of its declared inputs}
}

\p{You can mix both approaches in the same project, but package names must be unique.}
}

\subtree{
\title{Core Commands}
\pre{\startverb
flox build                      # Build all targets
flox build app docs             # Build specific targets
flox build -d /path/to/project  # Build in another directory
flox build -v                   # Verbose output
flox build .#hello              # Build specific Nix expression
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Development vs Runtime: The Two-Environment Pattern}
\p{A common workflow involves \strong{two separate environments}:}

\subtree{
\title{Development Environment (Build-Time)}
\p{Contains source code, build tools, and build definitions:}

\pre{\startverb
# project-dev/.flox/env/manifest.toml (in git with source code)
[install]
gcc.pkg-path = "gcc13"
make.pkg-path = "make"
python.pkg-path = "python311Full"
uv.pkg-path = "uv"

[build.myapp]
command = '''
  make build
  mkdir -p $out/bin
  cp build/myapp $out/bin/
'''
version = "1.0.0"
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Workflow:}}

\pre{\startverb
cd project-dev
flox activate
flox build myapp
flox publish -o myorg myapp
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Runtime Environment (Consume-Time)}
\p{Contains only the published package and runtime dependencies:}

\pre{\startverb
# project-runtime/.flox/env/manifest.toml (can push to FloxHub)
[install]
myapp.pkg-path = "myorg/myapp"  # The published package
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Workflow:}}

\pre{\startverb
cd project-runtime
flox init
flox install myorg/myapp
flox push  # Share runtime environment without source code
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Why separate environments?}}

\ul{
\li{Development environment: Heavy (build tools, source code, dev dependencies)}
\li{Runtime environment: Lightweight (only published package and runtime needs)}
\li{Security: Runtime environments don't expose source code}
\li{Clarity: Clear separation between building and consuming}
\li{Rollback: Can rollback the live generation of a runtime environment without affecting the development environment}
}

\p{\strong{Note}: You can also install published packages into existing environments (other projects, production environments, etc.), not just dedicated runtime environments.}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Manifest Builds}
\p{Flox treats a \strong{manifest build} as a short, deterministic Bash script that runs inside an activated environment and copies its deliverables into \code{\startverb $out\stopverb}. Anything copied there becomes a first-class, versioned package that can later be published and installed like any other catalog artifact.}

\subtree{
\title{Critical insights from real-world packaging:}
\ul{
\li{\strong{Build hooks don't run}: \code{\startverb [hook]\stopverb} scripts DO NOT execute during \code{\startverb flox build\stopverb} - only during interactive \code{\startverb flox activate\stopverb}}
\li{\strong{Guard env vars}: Always use \code{\startverb ${FLOX_ENV_CACHE:-}\stopverb} with default fallback in hooks to avoid build failures}
\li{\strong{Wrapper scripts pattern}: Create launcher scripts in \code{\startverb $out/bin/\stopverb} that set up runtime environment:}
\li{\strong{User config pattern}: Default to \code{\startverb ~/.myapp/\stopverb} for user configs, not \code{\startverb $FLOX_ENV_CACHE\stopverb} (packages are immutable)}
\li{\strong{Model/data directories}: Create user directories at runtime, not build time:}
\li{\strong{Python package strategy}: Don't bundle Python deps - include \code{\startverb requirements.txt\stopverb} and setup script:}
\li{\strong{Dual-environment workflow}: Use one environment for building (\code{\startverb project-dev/\stopverb}), another for consuming (\code{\startverb project-runtime/\stopverb}). See "Development vs Runtime: The Two-Environment Pattern" section above for details.}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Build Definition Syntax}
\pre{\startverb
[build.<name>]
command      = '''  # required – Bash, multiline string
  <your build steps>                 # e.g. cargo build, npm run build
  mkdir -p $out/bin
  cp path/to/artifact $out/bin/<name>
'''
version      = "1.2.3"               # optional
description  = "one-line summary"    # optional
sandbox      = "pure" | "off"        # default: off
runtime-packages = [ "id1", "id2" ]  # optional
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{One table per package.} Multiple \code{\startverb [build.*]\stopverb} tables let you publish, for example, a stripped release binary and a debug build from the same sources.}

\p{\strong{Bash only.} The script executes under \code{\startverb set -euo pipefail\stopverb}. If you need zsh or fish features, invoke them explicitly inside the script.}

\p{\strong{Environment parity.} Before your script runs, Flox performs the equivalent of \code{\startverb flox activate\stopverb} — so every tool listed in \code{\startverb [install]\stopverb} is on PATH.}

\p{\strong{Package groups and builds.} Only packages in the \code{\startverb toplevel\stopverb} group (default) are available during builds. Packages with explicit \code{\startverb pkg-group\stopverb} settings won't be accessible in build commands unless also installed to \code{\startverb toplevel\stopverb}.}

\p{\strong{Referencing other builds.} \code{\startverb ${other}\stopverb} expands to the \code{\startverb $out\stopverb} of \code{\startverb [build.other]\stopverb} and forces that build to run first, enabling multi-stage flows (e.g. vendoring → compilation).}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Purity and Sandbox Control}
\pre{\startverb
| sandbox value | Filesystem scope | Network | Typical use-case |
|---------------|------------------|---------|------------------|
| `"off"` (default) | Project working tree; complete host FS | allowed | Fast, iterative dev builds |
| `"pure"` | Git-tracked files only, copied to tmp | Linux: blocked<br>macOS: allowed | Reproducible, host-agnostic packages |
\stopverb}

\p{Pure mode highlights undeclared inputs early and is mandatory for builds intended for CI/CD publication. When a pure build needs pre-fetched artifacts (e.g. language modules) use a two-stage pattern:}

\pre{\startverb
[build.deps]
command  = '''go mod vendor -o $out/etc/vendor'''
sandbox  = "off"

[build.app]
command  = '''
  cp -r ${deps}/etc/vendor ./vendor
  go build ./...
  mkdir -p $out/bin
  cp app $out/bin/
'''
sandbox  = "pure"
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{$out Layout and Filesystem Hierarchy}
\p{Only files placed under \code{\startverb $out\stopverb} survive. Follow FHS conventions:}

\pre{\startverb
| Path | Purpose |
|------|---------|
| `$out/bin` / `$out/sbin` | CLI and daemon binaries (must be `chmod +x`) |
| `$out/lib`, `$out/libexec` | Shared libraries, helper programs |
| `$out/share/man` | Man pages (gzip them) |
| `$out/etc` | Configuration shipped with the package |
\stopverb}

\p{Scripts or binaries stored elsewhere will not end up on callers' paths.}
}

\subtree{
\title{Running Manifest Builds}
\pre{\startverb
# Build every target in the manifest
flox build

# Build a subset
flox build app docs

# Build a manifest in another directory
flox build -d /path/to/project
\stopverb}

\p{Results appear as immutable symlinks: \code{\startverb ./result-<name>\stopverb} → \code{\startverb /nix/store/...-<name>-<version>\stopverb}.}

\p{To execute a freshly built binary: \code{\startverb ./result-app/bin/app\stopverb}.}
}

\subtree{
\title{Multi-Stage Examples}
\subtree{
\title{Rust release binary plus source tar}
\pre{\startverb
[build.bin]
command = '''
  cargo build --release
  mkdir -p $out/bin
  cp target/release/myproject $out/bin/
'''
version = "0.9.0"

[build.src]
command = '''
  git archive --format=tar HEAD | gzip > $out/myproject-${bin.version}.tar.gz
'''
sandbox = "pure"
\stopverb}

\p{\code{\startverb ${bin.version}\stopverb} resolves because both builds share the same manifest.}
}

\subtree{
\title{Go with vendored dependencies}
\pre{\startverb
[build.vendor]
command = '''
  go mod vendor
  mkdir -p $out/vendor
  cp -r vendor/* $out/vendor/
'''
sandbox = "off"

[build.app]
command = '''
  cp -r ${vendor}/vendor ./
  go build -mod=vendor -o $out/bin/myapp
'''
sandbox = "pure"
\stopverb}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Trimming Runtime Dependencies}
\p{By default, every package in the \code{\startverb toplevel\stopverb} install-group becomes a runtime dependency of your build's closure—even if it was only needed at compile time.}

\p{Declare a minimal list instead:}

\pre{\startverb
[install]
clang.pkg-path = "clang"
pytest.pkg-path = "pytest"

[build.cli]
command = '''
  make
  mv build/cli $out/bin/
'''
runtime-packages = [ "clang" ]  # exclude pytest from runtime closure
\stopverb}

\p{Smaller closures copy faster and occupy less disk when installed on users' systems.}
}

\subtree{
\title{Version and Description Metadata}
\p{Flox surfaces these fields in \code{\startverb flox search\stopverb}, \code{\startverb flox show\stopverb}, and during publication.}

\pre{\startverb
[build.mytool]
version.command = "git describe --tags"
description = "High-performance log shipper"
\stopverb}

\p{Alternative forms:}

\pre{\startverb
version = "1.4.2"            # static string
version.file = "VERSION.txt" # read at build time
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Cross-Platform Considerations for Manifest Builds}
\p{\code{\startverb flox build\stopverb} targets the host's systems triple. To ship binaries for additional platforms you must trigger the build on machines (or CI runners) of those architectures:}

\pre{\startverb
linux-x86_64 → build → publish
darwin-aarch64 → build → publish
\stopverb}

\p{The manifest can remain identical across hosts.}
}

\subtree{
\title{Beyond Code — Packaging Assets}
\p{Any artifact that can be copied into \code{\startverb $out\stopverb} can be versioned and installed:}

\subtree{
\title{Nginx baseline config}
\pre{\startverb
[build.nginx_cfg]
command = '''mkdir -p $out/etc && cp nginx.conf $out/etc/'''
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Organization-wide .proto schema bundle}
\pre{\startverb
[build.proto]
command = '''
  mkdir -p $out/share/proto
  cp proto/**/*.proto $out/share/proto/
'''
\stopverb}

\p{Teams install these packages and reference them via \code{\startverb $FLOX_ENV/etc/nginx.conf\stopverb} or \code{\startverb $FLOX_ENV/share/proto\stopverb}.}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Nix Expression Builds}
\p{You can write a Nix expression instead of (or in addition to) defining a manifest build.}

\p{Put \code{\startverb *.nix\stopverb} build files in \code{\startverb .flox/pkgs/\stopverb} for Nix expression builds. Git add all files before building.}

\subtree{
\title{File Naming}
\ul{
\li{\code{\startverb hello.nix\stopverb} → package named \code{\startverb hello\stopverb}}
\li{\code{\startverb hello/default.nix\stopverb} → package named \code{\startverb hello\stopverb}}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Common Patterns}
\p{\strong{Shell Script}}

\pre{\startverb
{writeShellApplication, curl}:
writeShellApplication {
  name = "my-ip";
  runtimeInputs = [ curl ];
  text = ''curl icanhazip.com'';
}
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Your Project}}

\pre{\startverb
{ rustPlatform, lib }:
rustPlatform.buildRustPackage {
  pname = "my-app";
  version = "0.1.0";
  src = ../../.;
  cargoLock.lockFile = "${src}/Cargo.lock";
}
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Update Version}}

\pre{\startverb
{ hello, fetchurl }:
hello.overrideAttrs (finalAttrs: _: {
  version = "2.12.2";
  src = fetchurl {
    url = "mirror://gnu/hello/hello-${finalAttrs.version}.tar.gz";
    hash = "sha256-WpqZbcKSzCTc9BHO6H6S9qrluNE72caBm0x6nc4IGKs=";
  };
})
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Apply Patches}}

\pre{\startverb
{ hello }:
hello.overrideAttrs (oldAttrs: {
  patches = (oldAttrs.patches or []) ++ [ ./my.patch ];
})
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Hash Generation}
\ol{
\li{Use \code{\startverb hash = "";\stopverb}}
\li{Run \code{\startverb flox build\stopverb}}
\li{Copy hash from error message}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Commands}
\ul{
\li{\code{\startverb flox build\stopverb} - build all}
\li{\code{\startverb flox build .#hello\stopverb} - build specific}
\li{\code{\startverb git add .flox/pkgs/*\stopverb} - track files}
}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Language-Specific Build Examples}
\subtree{
\title{Python Application}
\pre{\startverb
[build.myapp]
command = '''
  mkdir -p $out/bin $out/share/myapp

  # Copy application code
  cp -r src/* $out/share/myapp/
  cp requirements.txt $out/share/myapp/

  # Create wrapper script
  cat > $out/bin/myapp << 'EOF'
#!/usr/bin/env bash
APP_ROOT="$(dirname "$(dirname "$(readlink -f "$0")")")"
export PYTHONPATH="$APP_ROOT/share/myapp:$PYTHONPATH"
exec python3 "$APP_ROOT/share/myapp/main.py" "$@"
EOF
  chmod +x $out/bin/myapp
'''
version = "1.0.0"
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Node.js Application}
\pre{\startverb
[build.webapp]
command = '''
  npm ci
  npm run build

  mkdir -p $out/share/webapp
  cp -r dist/* $out/share/webapp/
  cp package.json package-lock.json $out/share/webapp/

  cd $out/share/webapp && npm ci --production
'''
version = "1.0.0"
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Rust Binary}
\pre{\startverb
[build.cli]
command = '''
  cargo build --release
  mkdir -p $out/bin
  cp target/release/mycli $out/bin/
'''
version.command = "cargo metadata --no-deps --format-version 1 | jq -r '.packages[0].version'"
\stopverb}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Debugging Build Issues}
\subtree{
\title{Common Problems}
\p{\strong{Build hooks don't run}: \code{\startverb [hook]\stopverb} scripts DO NOT execute during \code{\startverb flox build\stopverb}}

\p{\strong{Package groups}: Only \code{\startverb toplevel\stopverb} group packages available during builds}

\p{\strong{Network access}: Pure builds can't access network on Linux}
}

\subtree{
\title{Debugging Steps}
\ol{
\li{Check build output: \code{\startverb flox build -v\stopverb}}
\li{Inspect result: \code{\startverb ls -la result-<name>/\stopverb}}
\li{Test binary: \code{\startverb ./result-<name>/bin/<name>\stopverb}}
\li{Check dependencies: \code{\startverb nix-store -q --references result-<name>\stopverb}}
}
}
}

